## The Fix — Strip Jackson classes from vendor jars during build

Add this to your `build.gradle`. It repacks the offending vendor jars during the `bootJar` packaging step, removing the shaded Jackson annotation classes before they get bundled into your fat jar:

```gradle
bootJar {
    // Strip old shaded Jackson annotation classes physically embedded inside
    // vendor jars (SBINEWPG_2023, PGPUtility, etc) that cause NoSuchFieldError
    // and NoSuchMethodError at runtime. These classes override jackson-annotations
    // 2.17.2 from BOOT-INF/lib/ with old pre-2.12 versions shaded inside the jar.
    excludeFiles {
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/SBINEWPG_2023') ||
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/PGPUtility') ||
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/BASE64DecoderData') ||
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/authentication-service') ||
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/encryption-decryption-service') ||
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/logging-service') ||
        it.path.contains('BOOT-INF/lib/notification-service')
    }
}
```

Wait — `excludeFiles` strips the whole jar, which breaks things. The correct approach for shaded classes is different. Here is the **proper working solution**:

## Correct Fix — Using Gradle's zip filtering in bootJar

Add this block to `build.gradle` (keep everything else the same, just add this):

```gradle
import org.springframework.boot.gradle.tasks.bundling.BootJar

tasks.named('bootJar', BootJar) {
    // Repack vendor jars to strip embedded jackson-annotation classes
    // that conflict with jackson-annotations 2.17.2
    from(configurations.runtimeClasspath.filter {
        it.name.contains('SBINEWPG_2023') ||
        it.name.contains('PGPUtility') ||
        it.name.contains('BASE64DecoderData') ||
        it.name.contains('authentication-service') ||
        it.name.contains('encryption-decryption-service') ||
        it.name.contains('logging-service') ||
        it.name.contains('notification-service')
    }.collect { vendorJar ->
        zipTree(vendorJar).matching {
            exclude 'com/fasterxml/jackson/**'
        }
    })
}
```

Actually, this approach also has complications. The cleanest, most reliable GitLab-only fix is a **CI pipeline step** that strips and repacks the jars before Gradle builds. Add this to your `java.gradle.yml` build script, **before** the `gradle clean build` line:

```yaml
script:
  - |
    set -eo pipefail

    # ── Strip shaded Jackson classes from vendor jars ──────────────────────────
    # SBINEWPG_2023 and other vendor jars bundle old jackson-annotations classes
    # internally (shaded), causing NoSuchFieldError/NoSuchMethodError at runtime
    # even when jackson-annotations 2.17.2 is on the classpath.
    # Solution: repack each vendor jar removing com/fasterxml/jackson/** entries.

    VENDOR_JAR_DIR="${CI_PROJECT_DIR}/lib"   # adjust to wherever your local jars are stored
    WORK_DIR="/tmp/jar-repack"
    mkdir -p "$WORK_DIR"

    for jar in "${VENDOR_JAR_DIR}"/*.jar; do
      jar_name=$(basename "$jar")
      echo "Checking $jar_name for shaded Jackson classes..."
      
      if jar tf "$jar" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "com/fasterxml/jackson"; then
        echo "  ⚠️  Found shaded Jackson in $jar_name — repacking..."
        mkdir -p "$WORK_DIR/$jar_name"
        cd "$WORK_DIR/$jar_name"
        jar xf "$jar"
        rm -rf com/fasterxml/jackson
        jar cf "$jar" .
        cd "$CI_PROJECT_DIR"
        echo "  ✅ Repacked $jar_name"
      else
        echo "  ✅ Clean: $jar_name"
      fi
    done

    # ── Now run the actual build ───────────────────────────────────────────────
    gradle clean build -x test -Pversion="${VERSION}"
```

